le side effects of using Salix alba f. caerulea, also known as blue willow bark, improperly include inducing allergic reactions in sensitive individuals due to its salicylate content, which can also cause nausea and stomach discomfort. Additionally, using this herbal remedy can exacerbate allergies in those who are already sensitive to salicylates or other compounds found in the plant, as it can trigger a range of symptoms including hives and itching. Furthermore, Salix alba f. caerulea may interact with certain medications, such as blood thinners and diabetes medications, by either enhancing or reducing their effects, which can be hazardous to one's health. In some cases, taking Salix alba f. caerulea can also cause gastrointestinal issues, including diarrhea, due to its high salicylate content and potential for gastrointestinal irritation. Overall, improper use of Salix alba f. caerulea can lead to a range of adverse effects, underscoring the importance of consulting with a healthcare professional before using this herbal remedy.", "family_slug": "salicaceae", "family_name": "Salicaceae", "what_description": "Salix alba f. caerulea is a cultivar of the white willow tree, belonging to the family Salicaceae. It is a deciduous tree characterized by a straight trunk, a broad, rounded crown, and a smooth, grayish-brown bark. The leaves are alternate, lanceolate, 3-6 cm long, and have a serrated margin, with a pale green color on the underside and a dark green color on the upper surface. The leaves are also pubescent on the lower surface and have a distinctive blue-green color on the upper surface, which is the result of a specific anthocyanin content. The tree typically grows 10-15 m tall and has a broad, spreading habit, with a moderate growth rate."}